<table bgcolor="#000000" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td width="10"><img width="10" height="1" src="images/space.gif" alt=""></td><td width="100%"><!-- spacer -->

<table cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor="#663399"  width="100%" align="center"><tr><td>
<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="1" border="0"  width="100%">
<tr>
	<td bgcolor="29003E" width="175" valign="top" nowrap>
	<a name="post276553"></a>
	
	<font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" ><b>Nenad</b></font><br>
	
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >Forum Apprentice</font><br>
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" ></font><br>
	<p>






	
	<td bgcolor="29003E" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" > <b></b></font>
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" >Well, I'm still interested why Istari's test and my test give different results. If I start with presumptions that his goranga tests were valid, which I have no reason not to think, then it is still question why he noticed those 2 concuss difference?<br />
<br />
As far as I understood their test, they were like this:<br />
<br />
IT1: non-wiz pull goranga, then wiz cast SoS, then wiz cast concuss untill aggro goes back to non-wiz ... that took 9 conc. <br />
<br />
IT2: non-wiz pull goranga, wiz cast first 10-20 conc, then wiz cast SoS,  then wiz cast concuss untill aggro goes back to non-wiz ... that took only 7 conc.<br />
<br />
It appears that there is some '2 conc buffer' of hate , which we discussed lot of times before in this thread, and which was basis for some people to say that "2 conc before first nuke is usefull"<br />
<br />
First thing of course would be to repeat those tests with some other mob and see if they produce same results. But until someone does that, we can go with presumption that we would have same results.<br />
<br />
Another thing that I'm definitelly certain of are results of my tests that show no existence of such buffer.  IF such buffer existed, in my T3 test I would have needed not 7 small nukes to regain aggro, but about 60 (!) small nukes ..... that is much,much greater difference than 7 compared to 9 , and that makes me certain that 2 conc (800) buffer does not exists. Not even 1 conc, not 1/10th of conc buffer exists.<br />
<br />
Now, what would be good explanation of Istari's test results, if we start from presumption that it is NOT 800 buffer?<br />
<br />
One idea that I got is that when FIRST time someone aggro mob, aggro of that first attack is multiplied by some factor, for example additional 30%. That would be quite logical thing for SoE to do, since it would help reduce ping-pong. For example, if you have two equal attacking chars (melee, nukers, whatever) attacking mob, if everything else would be same, eash hit/nuke could make mob change target.<br />
<br />
From our experience, it does not happen so often, ie unless we use really big nukes, with melee hits or small nukes you dont get mob so easily switched.<br />
<br />
One mechanism that SoE used is already explained in my tests, it is "first contact aggro" Bi .... so one who aggro mob first will have some additional aggro, and that may help reduce ping pong, ie may help mob to stay on first player if two players are doing equal aggro.  BuT as I hopefully proved in my tests, that initial aggro is not so big...it is about 100, which is about one melee round, certainly less that most nukes.<br />
<br />
So, another good mechanism that SoE could use would be to make first aggro (attack, nuke, whatever) multiplied for additional 30%. In that way if one player attack mob, and second player attack after him and they continue to produce similar aggro, mob will have more chance to remain on first player.<br />
<br />
In above IT1 goranga test, that would mean that first aggro from wiz was SoS, and instead of normal 7c it was (1.30*7)c for first nuke, making it 9c.   In IT2 test, first spell was conc, which adds 0 aggro, and in that case it added (1.30*0)aggro. When SoS was used, it was not first attack anymore, so it generated only 7c aggro.<br />
<br />
<br />
Now, this theory could be easily tested:<br />
<br />
T1: use SoS, then concuss<br />
-------------------------<br />
1) non-wiz pull mob<br />
2) WIZ cast SoS (which will generate normal SoS aggro + 30%, 9c)<br />
3) WIZ cast concuss, and count how many concuss are needed to remove aggro<br />
<br />
T2: use small nuke before first SoS, then concuss<br />
--------------------------------------------------------<br />
1) non-wiz pull mob<br />
2) WIZ cast "shock of fire" as very small aggro nuke, will generate shock aggro plus 30%, or 1.30*15=20, which can be ignored. <br />
3) WIZ cast SoS (which will generate normal SoS aggro, 7c)<br />
4) WIZ cast concuss, and count how many concuss are needed to remove aggro<br />
<br />
<br />
If it turns out that T1 will need 9 conc, and T2 (where wiz did more damage) will need only 7 conc to lose aggro, it would prove my theory.<br />
<br />
Now, I'm not sure if i'll have time to test this soon, but even if its not correct theory, I'm interested if anyone else have some other idea that would explain goranga test results, if it is not 800 buffer? :)</font></p>
	
	<p><p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" >__________________<br>
